    <h1> Linus Torvalds</h1>
    <p>The Creator of Linux</p>
    <figure>
        <img src="linu.jpeg" width="250" height="400">
        <figcaption>
            The Photograph of Linus Torvalds
        </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <h2>Biography</h2>
    <p>Linus Torvalds, (born December 28, 1969, Helsinki, Finland),
         Finnish computer scientist who was the principal force behind the development
          of the Linux operating system. At age 10 Torvalds began to dabble in
          computer programming on his grandfather's Commodore VIC-20.</p>

    <h2>Achievements</h2>
   <ul>
    <li><strong>1991</strong>-conceived and developed the Linux kernel</li>
    <li><strong>1994</strong>-March 14: Linux kernel version 1.0 was released, a significant milestone for the project, as it indicated that the kernel was stable enough for everyday use.</li>
    <li><strong>1997</strong>-October 9: Transmeta, a company that specialized in low-power microprocessors, was founded with Linus Torvalds as one of its co-founders.</li>
    <li><strong>1998</strong>-Torvalds was awarded the Nordic Free Software Award for his significant contributions to the free software movement.</li>
    <li><strong>2001</strong>-Linus Torvalds was named one of the MIT Technology Review's TR100, recognizing him as one of the top 100 innovators in the world under the age of 35.</li>
    <li><strong>2004</strong>-Linus Torvalds was awarded the Lovelace Medal from the British Computer Society for his outstanding contributions to the field of computing.</li>
    <li><strong>2010</strong>-December 11: Linus Torvalds was honored with the Free Software Foundation's Award for the Advancement of Free Software.</li>
    <li><strong>2012</strong>-June 15: Linus was one of the recipients of the Millennium Technology Prize, which is awarded for technological innovations that significantly improve the quality of human life.</li>
    <li><strong>2005</strong>-In a notable achievement, Linus Torvalds received the IEEE Computer Society's Computer Pioneer Award for his pioneering work in creating the Linux kernel and his contributions to open-source software.</li>
    
   </ul>
